  <chapter number="1" style="c" sid="MRK 1" />
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="1" style="v" sid="MRK 1:1" />The Beginning of the Good News<char style="sup">[a]</char> of Jesus Christ, Son of God<verse eid="MRK 1:1" />
    </para>
    <para style="m">
      <verse number="2" style="v" sid="MRK 1:2" />…Just as it had been written by the Prophet Isaiah:
    </para>
    <para style="pi" vid="MRK 1:2"></para>
    <para style="p" vid="MRK 1:2">See here—I will send my messenger</para>
    <para style="p" vid="MRK 1:2">To where your attention is fixated<char style="sup">[b]</char>,</para>
    <para style="p" vid="MRK 1:2">Who’ll prepare your way<verse eid="MRK 1:2"/>
    </para>
    <para style="pi" />    <!-- Spacer line. No verse associated with it. -->
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="3" style="v" sid="MRK 1:3" />The sound of shouting in the countryside<char style="sup">[d]</char>:
    </para>
    <para style="pi" vid="MRK 1:3">“Block off the road the Lord will take!</para>
    <para style="p" vid="MRK 1:3">Barricade the streets he’ll be on!”<char style="sup">[c]</char><verse eid="MRK 1:3"/>
    </para>
    <para style="pi" />    <!-- Spacer line. No verse associated with it. -->
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="4" style="v" sid="MRK 1:4" />John the Baptist came on the scene in the countryside<char style="sup">[d]</char> preaching a baptism—a
        water immersion-type of initiation ceremony—signifying a total commitment to a change in conduct to live
        the right way <char style="it">and signifying an initiation </char>into <char style="it">a</char> forgiveness
        of sins.<char style="sup">[e]</char> <verse eid="MRK 1:4" />
      <verse number="5" style="v" sid="MRK 1:5" />All<char style="sup">[f]</char> of the Judean region and everyone in Jerusalem were coming out and were
        being baptized by him in the Jordan River, one after another, while pouring their hearts out in confessing
        their sins out loud. <verse eid="MRK 1:5" />
      <verse number="6" style="v" sid="MRK 1:6" />John dressed himself in a camel hair outfit wrapped in a leather belt and for food ate grasshoppers and
        wild honey.<char style="sup">[g]</char> <verse eid="MRK 1:6" />
      <verse number="7" style="v" sid="MRK 1:7" />He preached, “One’s coming after me who’s greater than me, for whom I’m not worthy of bending over and
        unfastening one of the straps on his sandals. <verse eid="MRK 1:7" />
      <verse number="8" style="v" sid="MRK 1:8" />Me—I baptize in water, but he—he’ll baptize you in the Holy Spirit.”<verse eid="MRK 1:8" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="9" style="v" sid="MRK 1:9" />Jesus of Nazareth, Galilee came on the scene in those days and was baptized by John. <verse eid="MRK 1:9" />
      <verse number="10" style="v" sid="MRK 1:10" />As he came straight up out of the water, he saw the sky parting and the Spirit descending upon him like
        a dove.<char style="sup">[A]</char> <verse eid="MRK 1:10" />
      <verse number="11" style="v" sid="MRK 1:11" />A voice spoke from out of the sky, “You are my Beloved Son. I’m quite pleased with you.”<verse eid="MRK 1:11" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="12" style="v" sid="MRK 1:12" />Immediately the Spirit drove him into the countryside<char style="sup">[d]</char>. <verse eid="MRK 1:12" />
      <verse number="13" style="v" sid="MRK 1:13" />He was out there in the middle of nowhere<char style="sup">[d]</char> for forty days, being tempted<char
        style="sup">[B]</char> by Satan. He was fighting for his life,<char style="sup">[C]</char> and all the
        while the angels were attending to him.<verse eid="MRK 1:13" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="14" style="v" sid="MRK 1:14" />After John had been taken into custody, Jesus came to Galilee preaching God’s message of good news<char
        style="sup">[h]</char>, <verse eid="MRK 1:14" />
      <verse number="15" style="v" sid="MRK 1:15" />and saying that the time had arrived<char style="sup">[i]</char> and that God’s involvement with you
        (God’s kingdom) had drawn near; <char style="it">and saying</char>, <char style="wj">“Go about changing
        your ways</char><char style="sup">[j]</char><char style="wj"> and believing in the Good News</char><char
        style="sup">[h]</char><char style="wj">.”</char><verse eid="MRK 1:15" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="16" style="v" sid="MRK 1:16" />While passing by the Sea of Galilee, he saw Simon and his brother Andrew casting a net<char style="sup">[k]</char>,
        seeing that they were fishermen. <verse eid="MRK 1:16" />
      <verse number="17" style="v" sid="MRK 1:17" />Jesus said to them, <char style="wj">“Come be my followers, and I’ll make you into fishermen who fish
        for men.”</char> <verse eid="MRK 1:17" />
      <verse number="18" style="v" sid="MRK 1:18" />Right away they left their nets and followed him. <verse eid="MRK 1:18" />
      <verse number="19" style="v" sid="MRK 1:19" />He continued onwards a bit further and saw James, son of Zebedee, and his brother John, while they were
        in the boat mending the nets. <verse eid="MRK 1:19" />
      <verse number="20" style="v" sid="MRK 1:20" />Right away he called out to them, and they left their father Zebedee in the boat with the hired hands
        and departed to be his followers.<verse eid="MRK 1:20" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="21" style="v" sid="MRK 1:21" />They came to Capernaum, and without delay he started teaching in the synagogue there on the Sabbaths.<verse eid="MRK 1:21" />
      <verse number="22" style="v" sid="MRK 1:22" />They were amazed at his teaching, since he was teaching in a captivating manner<char style="sup">[l]</char>,
        and not like their designated teachers, the Scribes. <verse eid="MRK 1:22" />
      <verse number="23" style="v" sid="MRK 1:23" />In an instant, there was a man <char style="it">right there</char> in their synagogue with a demonic
        spirit<char style="sup">[m]</char>, and he screamed, <verse eid="MRK 1:23" />
      <verse number="24" style="v" sid="MRK 1:24" />”We have no beef with you,<char style="sup">[n]</char> Jesus of Nazareth; did you come to annihilate
        us? I know who you are: <char style="it">you’re</char> the Holy One of God.” <verse eid="MRK 1:24" />
      <verse number="25" style="v" sid="MRK 1:25" />Jesus <char style="it">sternly</char> took charge over him saying, <char style="wj">“Shut up and come
        out of him!” </char><verse eid="MRK 1:25" />
      <verse number="26" style="v" sid="MRK 1:26" />The demonic spirit<char style="sup">[m]</char> shook him real good, cried out in a loud voice, and then
        exited him. <verse eid="MRK 1:26" />
      <verse number="27" style="v" sid="MRK 1:27" />Everyone was amazed, to the extent that they began to discuss and argue among themselves, “<char style="it">Just</char>
        who is this guy?…Fresh teaching delivered in a captivating manner…He even takes charge over demonic spirits,
        and they obey him.” <verse eid="MRK 1:27" />
      <verse number="28" style="v" sid="MRK 1:28" />Immediately, the news about him spread to everyone in the entire area surrounding Galilee.<verse eid="MRK 1:28" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="29" style="v" sid="MRK 1:29" />Right after leaving the synagogue, they went with James and John to Simon and Andrew’s house. <verse eid="MRK 1:29" />
      <verse number="30" style="v" sid="MRK 1:30" />Simon’s mother-in-law was laid out with a fever, and immediately they spoke to <char style="it">Jesus</char>
        about her. <verse eid="MRK 1:30" />
      <verse number="31" style="v" sid="MRK 1:31" />He went over to her, took her hand, pulled her up, and the fever left, and she began to attend to their
        needs. <verse eid="MRK 1:31" />
      <verse number="32" style="v" sid="MRK 1:32" />When it was late in the day and the sun was setting, they began to bring him all those having something
        wrong with them<char style="sup">[o]</char> and the demon-possessed. <verse eid="MRK 1:32" />
      <verse number="33" style="v" sid="MRK 1:33" />The whole city gathered at the door, <verse eid="MRK 1:33" />
      <verse number="34" style="v" sid="MRK 1:34" />and he healed many of those who had something wrong with them consisting of a disease of one kind or
        another, and cast out many demons, and <char style="it">while casting them out </char>wasn’t letting
        the demons say anything, because they knew who he was.<verse eid="MRK 1:34" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="35" style="v" sid="MRK 1:35" />Early in the morning, before daybreak, he left and went out to a place where nobody was around and prayed
        and prayed there. <verse eid="MRK 1:35" />
      <verse number="36" style="v" sid="MRK 1:36" />Simon and those with him went out to hunt him down. <verse eid="MRK 1:36" />
      <verse number="37" style="v" sid="MRK 1:37" />They found him and, engaging him in conversation, said, “Everyone’s looking for you.” <verse eid="MRK 1:37" />
      <verse number="38" style="v" sid="MRK 1:38" />Continuing the conversation, he said, <char style="wj">“Let’s go somewhere else, to an area where there’s
        towns </char><char style="it"><char style="wj">in the vicinity</char></char><char style="wj">.”</char><verse eid="MRK 1:38" />
      <verse number="39" style="v" sid="MRK 1:39" />They went throughout all of Galilee preaching in the synagogues there and casting out demons.<verse eid="MRK 1:39" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="40" style="v" sid="MRK 1:40" />A leper approached him<char style="sup">[p]</char>, pleading with him, “If you so desire, you can purge
        this disease from me<char style="sup">[q]</char>.” <verse eid="MRK 1:40" />
      <verse number="41" style="v" sid="MRK 1:41" />He had pity on him, extended his hand, touched him, and pronounces, <char style="wj">“I do so desire;
        be purged of this disease.” </char><verse eid="MRK 1:41" />
      <verse number="42" style="v" sid="MRK 1:42" />Immediately it left him; he was purged of the disease. <verse eid="MRK 1:42" />
      <verse number="43" style="v" sid="MRK 1:43" />Without wasting any time, he sternly and with an inner indignation<char style="sup">[r]</char> gave him
        specific instructions and <char style="it">then</char> cut him loose<char style="sup">[s]</char>, <verse eid="MRK 1:43" />
      <verse number="44" style="v" sid="MRK 1:44" />telling him, <char style="wj">“Make sure you don’t say anything to anyone about this, but go your way
        and show yourself to the priest and bring along with you the offering that the Old Testament</char><char
        style="sup">[t]</char><char style="wj"> commands as an official submission for the certification of the
        purging of this disease.” </char><verse eid="MRK 1:44" />
      <verse number="45" style="v" sid="MRK 1:45" />But he departed and began going around enthusiastically telling lots of people what had happened and
        spreading the story and its acclamation around, resulting in him no longer being able to enter a city,
        but instead having to stay outside in the countryside.</para>
    <para style="p" vid="MRK 1:45">And they began to come to him from every direction.<verse eid="MRK 1:45"/>
    </para>
