      <char style="ft"><char style="it">He was fighting for his life…</char>Lit: <char style="it">he was with the wild beasts</char>.
        This is an idiom used in both the OT and NT (Ref. Ps. 22:12,13, 1 Cor. 15:32), and means, <char style="it">I
        was fighting for my life, </char>or, <char style="it">I had my back against the wall, </char>or, <char
        style="it">I was between a rock and a hard spot.</char></char>
    </note>
  <chapter eid="MRK 1" />
  <!--   **********   -->
  <!--   Chapter  2   -->
  <!--   **********   -->
  <chapter number="2" style="c" sid="MRK 2" />
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="1" style="v" sid="MRK 2:1" />Several days after entering Capernaum, word got out that he was staying in a house <char style="it">there</char>.<verse eid="MRK 2:1" />
      <verse number="2" style="v" sid="MRK 2:2" />Many converged on it, to the extent that nobody could get in or out of the door anymore, and he kept
        on speaking the word <char style="it">of God</char> to them. <verse eid="MRK 2:2" />
      <verse number="3" style="v" sid="MRK 2:3" />Four men arrived carrying a stretcher that had someone who was paralyzed on it. <verse eid="MRK 2:3" />
      <verse number="4" style="v" sid="MRK 2:4" />Not being able to carry him through the crowd, they pulled away the roof where he was and dug out a hole
        in order to lower the stretcher on which the paralyzed fellow was lying. <verse eid="MRK 2:4" />
      <verse number="5" style="v" sid="MRK 2:5" />Seeing their faith, Jesus said to the one paralyzed, <char style="wj">“Son, your sins are forgiven.”
        </char><verse eid="MRK 2:5" />
      <verse number="6" style="v" sid="MRK 2:6" />Some of the designated teachers<char style="sup">[a]</char> were sitting there mulling this over in their
        hearts, <verse eid="MRK 2:6" />
      <verse number="7" style="v" sid="MRK 2:7" />”How can he talk that way to this guy? He’s blaspheming; who’s able to forgive sins, except for the one-and-only
        God?” <verse eid="MRK 2:7" />
      <verse number="8" style="v" sid="MRK 2:8" />Immediately coming to the realization in his spirit exactly what they had thought up, Jesus engages them
        in conversation, <char style="wj">“Why did you, inside of yourselves, think these things up? </char><verse eid="MRK 2:8" />
      <verse number="9" style="v" sid="MRK 2:9" /><char style="wj">What’s easier to say to the one paralyzed, ‘Your sins are forgiven,’ or, ‘Get up, take
        your stretcher, and walk around’? </char><verse eid="MRK 2:9" />
      <verse number="10" style="v" sid="MRK 2:10" /><char style="wj">But so that you would know that the Man</char><char style="sup">[b]</char><char style="wj">
        has the authority on earth to forgive sins…” </char>he <char style="it">turns and</char> speaks to the
        paralyzed fellow, <verse eid="MRK 2:10" />
      <verse number="11" style="v" sid="MRK 2:11" /><char style="wj">”…I say to you, pick up your stretcher and go on home.” </char><verse eid="MRK 2:11" />
      <verse number="12" style="v" sid="MRK 2:12" />And in front of everybody he got up, without delay picked up his stretcher, and left, to everyone’s amazement
        and to their glorification of God saying, “We’ve never seen anything like this before.”<verse eid="MRK 2:12" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="13" style="v" sid="MRK 2:13" />Again, he ventured out near the sea. Everyone in the crowd started coming to him, and he began teaching
        them. <verse eid="MRK 2:13" />
      <verse number="14" style="v" sid="MRK 2:14" />As he was passing through, he saw Levi <char style="it">son</char> of Alphaeus sitting at the customs
        table<char style="sup">[A]</char>, and tells him directly, “Be my follower.<char style="sup">[c]</char>”
        And he got up and became his follower. <verse eid="MRK 2:14" />
      <verse number="15" style="v" sid="MRK 2:15" />As he sat down to dine<char style="sup">[B]</char> at home, many tax collectors and <char style="it">other
        </char>sinners gathered there to eat with Jesus. <verse eid="MRK 2:15" />
      <verse number="16" style="v" sid="MRK 2:16" />The designated teachers, the ones affiliated with<char style="it"> </char>the Pharisees, observing that
        he takes meals with sinners and tax collectors, were saying to his disciples, “How is it that he dines
        with the tax collectors and <char style="it">other</char> sinners?” <verse eid="MRK 2:16" />
      <verse number="17" style="v" sid="MRK 2:17" />Jesus heard <char style="it">this</char> and said to them, <char style="wj">“Healthy people don’t need
        a doctor, but those who have something wrong with them do. I didn’t come to call </char><char style="it"><char
        style="wj">on</char></char><char style="wj"> those right with God but rather </char><char style="it"><char
        style="wj">on</char></char><char style="wj"> sinners.”</char><verse eid="MRK 2:17" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="18" style="v" sid="MRK 2:18" />John’s disciples and the Pharisees were fasting, and they approached him with a question, “What’s the
        reason that John’s disciples fast and the Pharisees’ disciples fast, but your disciples don’t fast?”<verse eid="MRK 2:18" />
      <verse number="19" style="v" sid="MRK 2:19" />Jesus said, <char style="wj">“The groom’s cronies can’t fast when the groom’s around, </char><char style="it"><char
        style="wj">can they</char></char><char style="wj">? As long as the groom is with them, they’re not able
        to fast. </char><verse eid="MRK 2:19" />
      <verse number="20" style="v" sid="MRK 2:20" /><char style="wj">But there’ll come a day</char><char style="sup">[d]</char><char style="wj"> when the
        groom is taken away, and that’s the day they’ll start fasting.” </char><verse eid="MRK 2:20" />
      <verse number="21" style="v" sid="MRK 2:21" /><char style="wj">No one uses a patch made from new material to patch an old garment with; otherwise,
        the new </char><char style="it"><char style="wj">material</char></char><char style="wj"> will wind up
        tearing itself away from the old, and a worse gap will appear. </char><verse eid="MRK 2:21" />
      <verse number="22" style="v" sid="MRK 2:22" /><char style="wj">And no one puts freshly-squeezed grape juice</char><char style="sup">[C]</char><char
        style="wj"> into old wineskins; otherwise, the wine will cause the skins to burst, and </char><char style="it"><char
        style="wj">both</char></char><char style="wj"> the wine and the skins will be ruined. Rather, grape juice
        </char><char style="it"><char style="wj">goes</char></char><char style="wj"> into new wine skins.”</char><verse eid="MRK 2:22" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="23" style="v" sid="MRK 2:23" />He happened to be passing through the grain fields on days which were Sabbath days, and his disciples
        began to make their way through the fields stripping the grain off the heads of the stalks<char style="sup">[D]</char>.<verse eid="MRK 2:23" />
      <verse number="24" style="v" sid="MRK 2:24" />The Pharisees proceeded to say to him, “<char style="it">Take a</char> look—they’re doing what’s forbidden
        on the Sabbath.” <verse eid="MRK 2:24" />
      <verse number="25" style="v" sid="MRK 2:25" />Looking deeper at the situation, he said to them, <char style="wj">“Didn’t you read about what David
        did when the need arose and he got hungry</char><char style="sup">[e]</char><char style="wj">—and so
        did those who were with him? </char><verse eid="MRK 2:25" />
      <verse number="26" style="v" sid="MRK 2:26" /><char style="wj">How, when Abiathar was high priest, he entered the house of God and ate the holy bread</char><char
        style="sup">[E]</char><char style="wj">, which no one’s allowed to eat except the priests, and—not only
        that—he passed it out to those who were with him?”</char> <verse eid="MRK 2:26" />
      <verse number="27" style="v" sid="MRK 2:27" />He summarized, <char style="wj">“The Sabbath came into being for </char><char style="it"><char style="wj">the
        benefit of</char></char><char style="wj"> mankind, and not mankind for </char><char style="it"><char
        style="wj">the benefit of</char></char><char style="wj"> the Sabbath, </char><verse eid="MRK 2:27" />
      <verse number="28" style="v" sid="MRK 2:28" /><char style="wj">the result being that the Man is also master over the Sabbath.”</char><verse eid="MRK 2:28" />
    </para>
  <!--   .........   -->
  <!--   Footnotes   -->
  <!--   .........   -->
    <note caller="[a]" style="f">
      <char style="fk">[a]</char>
      <char style="ft"><char style="it">designated teachers…</char>Lit: <char style="it">Scribes</char></char>
    </note>
    <note caller="[b]" style="f">
      <char style="fk">[b]</char>
      <char style="ft"><char style="it">the Man…</char>Lit: <char style="it">the Son of Man</char>. Ref. note in Matt. 8:20.</char>
    </note>
    <note caller="[c]" style="f">
      <char style="fk">[c]</char>
      <char style="ft"><char style="it">Be my follower…</char>Lit: <char style="it">follow me</char></char>
    </note>
    <note caller="[d]" style="f">
      <char style="fk">[d]</char>
      <char style="ft"><char style="it">But there’ll come a day…</char>Lit: <char style="it">But days will come</char></char>
    </note>
    <note caller="[e]" style="f">
      <char style="fk">[e]</char>
      <char style="ft"><char style="it">he got hungry…</char>Impl: <char style="it">he got hungry by his own right</char>, or,
        <char style="it">he got hungry by his own doing</char></char>
      <char style="fp"></char>
    </note>
    <note caller="[A]" style="f">
      <char style="fk">[A]</char>
      <char style="ft"><char style="it">customs table…</char>Also: <char style="it">custom house</char>,<char style="it"> revenue
        office</char>, or <char style="it">tax office</char>. Nowadays, we visit places like tag agencies or
        license plate offices. The concept is similar, the details vastly different, of course.</char>
    </note>
    <note caller="[B]" style="f">
      <char style="fk">[B]</char>
      <char style="ft"><char style="it">sat down to dine…</char>Lit: <char style="it">And he happens to recline at his house</char>.
        They reclined to partake of the meal, taking their time at it and enjoying the company of those dining
        them. Also, the GT insinuates that, once the sinners heard that Jesus had reclined for a meal, they came
        and joined him at the meal.</char>
    </note>
    <note caller="[C]" style="f">
      <char style="fk">[C]</char>
      <char style="ft"><char style="it">freshly-squeezed grape juice…</char>Lit: <char style="it">new wine</char>. The Gk. word
        for wine means either grape juice (no preservatives, of course) or wine. The distinction in ancient times
        is that grape juice is simply wine which hasn’t fermented yet; freshly-squeezed grape juice will invariably
        ferment into wine (or vinegar if not done properly). The fermentation of the juice into wine yields gases,
        and since the skins are sealed shut, such gases cause an increase in pressure, which causes a new skin
        to stretch, and therefore the total volume in the sealed container to increase, thereby reducing the
        pressure. Old skins, those which have been used once already for making wine, have been stretched fully
        and do not shrink after the wine has been poured out of them. When grape juice is fermented in them a
        second time, since they have already been stretched to their maximum extent, and are not capable of stretching
        any more, the pressure buildup from the second fermentation cannot be relieved and causes the skins to
        burst.</char>
    </note>
    <note caller="[D]" style="f">
      <char style="fk">[D]</char>
      <char style="ft"><char style="it">stripping the grain off the heads of the stalks</char>…Walking through the fields and
        eating the heads of wheat, barley, etc.; this is permitted under OT law (ref. Lev. 19:9-10, Deut. 24:19-21,
        and others).</char>
    </note>
    <note caller="[E]" style="f">
      <char style="fk">[E]</char>
      <char style="ft"><char style="it">holy bread…</char>The <char style="it">holy bread</char> here is the showbread. This
        is bread which was placed on a table and was always present in the Temple in Jerusalem, as required by
        the OT (ref. Exod. 25:30, Matt. 12:4).</char>
    </note>
  <chapter eid="MRK 2" />
  <!--   **********   -->
  <!--   Chapter  3   -->
  <!--   **********   -->
  <chapter number="3" style="c" sid="MRK 3" />
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="1" style="v" sid="MRK 3:1" />Yet again he introduced himself to those in the synagogue and attended a meeting<char style="sup">[a]</char>.
        There was a man there with a shriveled-up<char style="sup">[b]</char> hand, <verse eid="MRK 3:1" />
      <verse number="2" style="v" sid="MRK 3:2" />and they were watching him closely, to see if he was going to heal him on the Sabbath, so that they’d
        have something to accuse him of. <verse eid="MRK 3:2" />
      <verse number="3" style="v" sid="MRK 3:3" />He addressed the man with the shriveled-up hand, <char style="wj">“Get up and stand </char><char style="it"><char
        style="wj">front and</char></char><char style="wj"> center.”</char> <verse eid="MRK 3:3" />
      <verse number="4" style="v" sid="MRK 3:4" />He challenged them, <char style="wj">“Is it permissible on the Sabbath to do a good deed or to do bad,
        to save someone’s life or to kill someone?” </char>They remained silent. <verse eid="MRK 3:4" />
      <verse number="5" style="v" sid="MRK 3:5" />He looked all around, staring at them in fury, being deeply grieved over the callousness of their hearts,
        and said to the man intently, <char style="wj">“Stretch your hand out.” </char>He stretched it out, and
        his hand was restored. <verse eid="MRK 3:5" />
      <verse number="6" style="v" sid="MRK 3:6" />After the Pharisees departed, they wasted no time in meeting with the Herodians about him, <char style="it">to
        figure out</char> how they could kill him.<verse eid="MRK 3:6" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="7" style="v" sid="MRK 3:7" />Jesus, accompanied by his disciples, ventured over to the sea, and a great many followed him from Galilee,
        and from Judea, <verse eid="MRK 3:7" />
      <verse number="8" style="v" sid="MRK 3:8" />and from Jerusalem, and from Idumea, and from the other side of the Jordan <char style="it">River</char>,
        and from <char style="it">the areas</char> around Tyre and Sidon—a great many, hearing about how much
        he was doing, went to him. <verse eid="MRK 3:8" />
      <verse number="9" style="v" sid="MRK 3:9" />And because of the crowd, he spoke to his disciples about getting a boat, so that they wouldn’t press
        in on him. <verse eid="MRK 3:9" />
      <verse number="10" style="v" sid="MRK 3:10" />Indeed, he treated many, resulting in them mobbing him<char style="sup">[c]</char> in order that they
        might receive a touch from him, whoever was getting the tar beaten out of him by disease or whatnot<char
        style="sup">[d]</char>. <verse eid="MRK 3:10" />
      <verse number="11" style="v" sid="MRK 3:11" />And, time and time again, the demonic spirits<char style="sup">[e]</char>, when they saw him, prostrated
        themselves before him in homage and screamed out, “You are the Son of God!” <verse eid="MRK 3:11" />
      <verse number="12" style="v" sid="MRK 3:12" />And, time and time again, he was sternly silencing them so they would not cause him to be plainly known
        <char style="it">as such</char>.<verse eid="MRK 3:12" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="13" style="v" sid="MRK 3:13" />He hiked up a mountain and summoned those whom he had been wanting <char style="it">to have as his disciples</char>,
        and they came to him. <verse eid="MRK 3:13" />
      <verse number="14" style="v" sid="MRK 3:14" />He made twelve<char style="sup">[A]</char>, <char style="it">and he made them</char> so that they would
        be with him and so that he could send them out to preach <char style="it">his message</char> <verse eid="MRK 3:14" />
      <verse number="15" style="v" sid="MRK 3:15" />and to have authority to cast out demons<char style="sup">[B]</char>. <verse eid="MRK 3:15" />
      <verse number="16" style="v" sid="MRK 3:16" /><char style="sup">[A]</char>He assigned the name “Peter<char style="sup">[C]</char>” to Simon, <verse eid="MRK 3:16" />
      <verse number="17" style="v" sid="MRK 3:17" />and <char style="it">there was</char> James son of Zebedee and his brother John, to whom he assigned
        the name “Sons of Thunder<char style="sup">[f]</char>,” <verse eid="MRK 3:17" />
      <verse number="18" style="v" sid="MRK 3:18" />Andrew, Philip, Bartholomew, Matthew, Thomas, James son of Alphaeus, Thaddeus, Simon the Canaaanite (i.e.,
        Zealot), <verse eid="MRK 3:18" />
      <verse number="19" style="v" sid="MRK 3:19" />and Judas Iscariot, his betrayer.<verse eid="MRK 3:19" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="20" style="v" sid="MRK 3:20" />Now he came to a house. Once again, the crowd converged on it, resulting in them not being able to get
        a bite<char style="sup">[g]</char> to eat. <verse eid="MRK 3:20" />
      <verse number="21" style="v" sid="MRK 3:21" />When the neighbors<char style="sup">[h]</char> caught wind of this, they came out to get him under control<char
        style="sup">[i]</char>, since they had been saying <char style="it">all along</char> that he’s lost his
        mind. <verse eid="MRK 3:21" />
      <verse number="22" style="v" sid="MRK 3:22" />And the designated teachers, the Scribes, made the journey from Jerusalem<char style="it"> </char>and
        had been saying that he’s possessed by the Chief Demon<char style="sup">[j]</char> himself, and that,
        by means of the chief, he casts out the underling-demons. <verse eid="MRK 3:22" />
      <verse number="23" style="v" sid="MRK 3:23" />He called them over and began to teach them by using analogies<char style="sup">[k]</char>: <char style="wj">“How
        can one demon cast out another demon</char><char style="sup">[l]</char><char style="wj">? </char><verse eid="MRK 3:23" />
      <verse number="24" style="v" sid="MRK 3:24" /><char style="wj">If a kingdom is divided </char><char style="it"><char style="wj">into parts which are</char></char><char
        style="wj"> </char><char style="it"><char style="wj">pitted</char></char><char style="wj"> against each
        other</char><char style="sup">[l]</char><char style="wj">, that kingdom will fall apart. </char><verse eid="MRK 3:24" />
      <verse number="25" style="v" sid="MRK 3:25" /><char style="wj">And if an organization is divided </char><char style="it"><char style="wj">into parts
        which are pitted</char></char><char style="wj"> against each other</char><char style="sup">[m]</char><char
        style="wj">, that organization will fall apart. </char><verse eid="MRK 3:25" />
      <verse number="26" style="v" sid="MRK 3:26" /><char style="wj">And if Satan has one demon oppose another demon, and they split </char><char style="it"><char
        style="wj">into hostile factions</char></char><char style="wj">, his </char><char style="it"><char style="wj">kingdom</char></char><char
        style="wj"> will fall apart—and that’s the end of that</char><char style="sup">[n]</char><char style="wj">.
        </char><verse eid="MRK 3:26" />
      <verse number="27" style="v" sid="MRK 3:27" /><char style="wj">More to the point—no one can enter the tough guy’s house, unless he first subdues the
        tough guy.</char><char style="sup">[D]</char><char style="wj"> </char><verse eid="MRK 3:27" />
      <verse number="28" style="v" sid="MRK 3:28" /><char style="wj">I tell you for sure, that ornery folk</char><char style="sup">[o]</char><char style="wj">
        will be forgiven of anything and of the random blasphemies that they blurt out</char><char style="sup">[p]</char><char
        style="wj">, </char><verse eid="MRK 3:28" />
      <verse number="29" style="v" sid="MRK 3:29" /><char style="wj">but if anyone were to blaspheme the Holy Spirit</char><char style="sup">[E]</char><char
        style="wj">, he won’t ever be forgiven—he’s guilty of an eternal sin.”</char> <verse eid="MRK 3:29" />
      <verse number="30" style="v" sid="MRK 3:30" /><char style="it">He said all this </char>because they were going about saying, “He has a demonic spirit<char
        style="sup">[d]</char>.”<verse eid="MRK 3:30" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="31" style="v" sid="MRK 3:31" />His mother and brothers came and were standing outside and sent him word, calling on him. <verse eid="MRK 3:31" />
      <verse number="32" style="v" sid="MRK 3:32" />Seated around him was a crowd, and they said to him, “Hey, your mother and your brothers are outside
        looking for you.” <verse eid="MRK 3:32" />
      <verse number="33" style="v" sid="MRK 3:33" />Surprisingly, he replied, <char style="wj">“Who is my mother and my brothers?”</char> <verse eid="MRK 3:33" />
      <verse number="34" style="v" sid="MRK 3:34" />He looked around at those sitting in a circle around him and said, <char style="wj">“Take a look here—my
        mother and my brothers.” </char><verse eid="MRK 3:34" />
      <verse number="35" style="v" sid="MRK 3:35" /><char style="wj">Whoever does the will of God, that’s my brother and sister and mother.”</char><verse eid="MRK 3:35" />
    </para>
