  <chapter number="7" style="c" sid="MRK 7" />
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="1" style="v" sid="MRK 7:1" />The Pharisees and some of the designed teachers<char style="sup">[a]</char> came from Jerusalem and congregated
        around him. <verse eid="MRK 7:1" />
      <verse number="2" style="v" sid="MRK 7:2" />They were observing some of his disciples taking their meals with defiled<char style="sup">[A]</char>
        hands (that is, with unwashed hands), <verse eid="MRK 7:2" />
      <verse number="3" style="v" sid="MRK 7:3" />since the Pharisees and all the Jews won’t eat if they haven’t washed their hands up to their wrists,
        adhering to the time-honored traditions<char style="sup">[b]</char>, <verse eid="MRK 7:3" />
      <verse number="4" style="v" sid="MRK 7:4" />and if they come from the marketplace or the town square, they won’t eat until they take a <char style="it">ceremonial</char>
        bath; plus they adhere to many more things that have been handed down through the years…the <char style="it">ceremonial</char>
        washing of wine chalices, of jugs, of utensils— <verse eid="MRK 7:4" />
      <verse number="5" style="v" sid="MRK 7:5" />and the Pharisees and designated teachers<char style="sup">[a]</char> asked him, “Why is it that your
        disciples aren’t in the habit of observing the time-honored traditions, but eat their meals with tainted
        hands?” <verse eid="MRK 7:5" />
      <verse number="6" style="v" sid="MRK 7:6" />He said, <char style="wj">“Isaiah sure was right when he prophesied about you—the hypocrites—as it is
        written:</char></para>
    <para style="pi" vid="MRK 7:6"></para>
    <para style="pi" vid="MRK 7:6"><char style="wj">“This people honors Me with their lips</char></para>
    <para style="pi" vid="MRK 7:6"><char style="wj">But their hearts are held at a distance from me.</char><verse eid="MRK 7:6"/>
    </para>
    <para style="pi">
      <verse number="7" style="v" sid="MRK 7:7" /><char style="wj">So they worship Me to no avail</char>
    </para>
    <para style="pi" vid="MRK 7:7"><char style="wj">Teaching man’s commandments</char><char style="sup">[c]</char><char style="wj">.</char><verse eid="MRK 7:7"/>
    </para>
    <para style="pi" />    <!-- Spacer line. No verse associated with it. -->
    <para style="m">
      <verse number="8" style="v" sid="MRK 7:8" /><char style="wj">”Abandoning the commandment of God, you adhere to the tradition of men.” </char><verse eid="MRK 7:8" />
      <verse number="9" style="v" sid="MRK 7:9" />He kept on going, <char style="wj">“Great job rejecting the commandment of God in order to adhere to
        your traditions. </char><verse eid="MRK 7:9" />
      <verse number="10" style="v" sid="MRK 7:10" /><char style="wj">Now, the Old Testament says,</char><char style="sup">[d]</char><char style="wj"> ‘Financially
        support your mother and father</char><char style="sup">[e]</char><char style="wj">’, and ‘Let he who
        bad-mouths his mother or father be put to death</char><char style="sup">[f]</char><char style="wj">’.
        </char><verse eid="MRK 7:10" />
      <verse number="11" style="v" sid="MRK 7:11" /><char style="wj">But you all say, ‘That payment which I was obligated to send you has instead been designated
        as an offering to God</char><char style="sup">[g]</char><char style="wj">’, </char><verse eid="MRK 7:11" />
      <verse number="12" style="v" sid="MRK 7:12" /><char style="it"><char style="wj">meaning that such a person </char></char><char style="wj">is off the
        hook for sending funds to his mother and father. </char><verse eid="MRK 7:12" />
      <verse number="13" style="v" sid="MRK 7:13" /><char style="wj">You’re disregarding the word of God by the tradition handed down to you. You do all
        sorts of things like that.”</char><verse eid="MRK 7:13" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="14" style="v" sid="MRK 7:14" />He summoned the crowd and kept with the subject, saying, <char style="wj">“Everyone, listen to me and
        get ahold of this. </char><verse eid="MRK 7:14" />
      <verse number="15" style="v" sid="MRK 7:15" /><char style="wj">There’s nothing outside of a person which, by going into him, can defile him; but rather
        those things which proceed out of a person are what defiles the person.” </char><verse eid="MRK 7:15" />
      <verse number="16" style="v" sid="MRK 7:16" /><char style="sup">[B]</char><verse eid="MRK 7:16" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="17" style="v" sid="MRK 7:17" />When he entered a house, away from the crowd, his disciples started asking him about the illustration<char
        style="sup">[h]</char>. <verse eid="MRK 7:17" />
      <verse number="18" style="v" sid="MRK 7:18" />He said to them, <char style="wj">“You don’t get it either? Don’t you know that everything on the outside
        which goes into a person can’t defile him, </char><verse eid="MRK 7:18" />
      <verse number="19" style="v" sid="MRK 7:19" /><char style="wj">because it doesn’t go into his heart, but instead goes into his intestines, and then
        leaves him going into the toilet (</char><char style="it"><char style="wj">thereby</char></char><char
        style="wj"> </char><char style="it"><char style="wj">declaring that</char></char><char style="wj">, </char><char
        style="it"><char style="wj">henceforth</char></char><char style="wj">, you’re allowed to eat any kind
        of food</char><char style="sup">[C]</char><char style="wj">)?”</char> <verse eid="MRK 7:19" />
      <verse number="20" style="v" sid="MRK 7:20" />He continued on saying, <char style="wj">“The stuff which proceeds out of a person—that’s what defiles
        the person. </char><verse eid="MRK 7:20" />
      <verse number="21" style="v" sid="MRK 7:21" /><char style="wj">Indeed, from within a person’s heart comes out of it the conniving</char><char style="sup">[i]</char><char
        style="wj"> </char><char style="it"><char style="wj">common to mankind</char></char><char style="wj">…sexual
        immorality</char><char style="sup">[j]</char><char style="wj">, thievery, murder, </char><verse eid="MRK 7:21" />
      <verse number="22" style="v" sid="MRK 7:22" /><char style="wj">adultery, greed, utter corruption</char><char style="sup">[k]</char><char style="wj">,
        intentional misleading</char><char style="sup">[l]</char><char style="wj">, strong out-of-control desire</char><char
        style="sup">[m]</char><char style="wj">, evil trains of thought</char><char style="sup">[n]</char><char
        style="wj">, blasphemy or bad-mouthing, arrogance</char><char style="sup">[o]</char><char style="wj">,
        reckless stupidity</char><char style="sup">[p]</char><char style="wj">. </char><verse eid="MRK 7:22" />
      <verse number="23" style="v" sid="MRK 7:23" /><char style="wj">All of these inner evils proceed to the outside and defile a person.”</char><verse eid="MRK 7:23" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="24" style="v" sid="MRK 7:24" />He wrapped things up there and left for the region of Tyre. He entered a house, <char style="it">since</char>
        he wasn’t wanting to have direct contact with anyone. <verse eid="MRK 7:24" />
      <verse number="25" style="v" sid="MRK 7:25" />But instead, without delay a woman who had a daughter who was <char style="it">overcome with</char> having
        a demonic spirit heard about him and came and fell at his feet. <verse eid="MRK 7:25" />
      <verse number="26" style="v" sid="MRK 7:26" />But the woman was a non-Jew<char style="sup">[q]</char>, a Syro-Phoenician by nationality. She <char
        style="it">drove home her point</char> asking him if he’d cast the demon out of his daughter. <verse eid="MRK 7:26" />
      <verse number="27" style="v" sid="MRK 7:27" />And he <char style="it">drove home his point</char> saying to her,
    </para>
    <para style="p" vid="MRK 7:27"><char style="wj">“Let the children </char><char style="it"><char style="wj">eat</char></char><char style="wj">
        until they’re full first, since it wouldn’t be right to take the children’s bread and toss it to the
        dogs.</char><char style="sup">[D]</char><char style="wj">”</char><verse eid="MRK 7:27"/>
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="28" style="v" sid="MRK 7:28" />But <char style="it">after some thought </char>she replied, “Lord, even the dogs <char style="it">groveling</char>
        under the table are fed from the children’s crumbs.”<verse eid="MRK 7:28" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="29" style="v" sid="MRK 7:29" />He said to her, <char style="wj">“On account of this statement, go your way: the demon has gone out of
        your daughter, for good.”</char><verse eid="MRK 7:29" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="30" style="v" sid="MRK 7:30" />After arriving back home, she found the child bedfast and the demon gone for good.<verse eid="MRK 7:30" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="31" style="v" sid="MRK 7:31" />Again, he left Tyre and went through Sidon to the Sea of Galilee, to the central area of Decapolis. <verse eid="MRK 7:31" />
      <verse number="32" style="v" sid="MRK 7:32" />They brought him a man who was deaf and who could barely speak, and they asked him to lay his hand on
        him. <verse eid="MRK 7:32" />
      <verse number="33" style="v" sid="MRK 7:33" />He took him aside, <char style="it">in order to be</char> away from the crowd and to have some privacy,
        and he stuck his fingers in his ears, and, after he spat, touched <char style="it">all around</char>
        his tongue. <verse eid="MRK 7:33" />
      <verse number="34" style="v" sid="MRK 7:34" />He looked up in the sky, let out a groan from deep within, and said to him <char style="wj">“Effatha!”</char>,
        which means, <char style="wj">“Be opened up, all the way!”</char>. <verse eid="MRK 7:34" />
      <verse number="35" style="v" sid="MRK 7:35" />His hearing was restored,<char style="sup">[r]</char> and his speaking impairment was broken,<char style="sup">[s]</char>
        and he began to speak correctly. <verse eid="MRK 7:35" />
      <verse number="36" style="v" sid="MRK 7:36" />He gave them orders, in no uncertain terms, not to tell anyone, but the more he would leave orders, the
        more they went about spreading the word<char style="it"> to others</char>.<char style="sup">[E]</char><verse eid="MRK 7:36" />
      <verse number="37" style="v" sid="MRK 7:37" />They were <char style="it">continuously</char> overflowing with amazement saying, “All the good he’s
        accomplished—he even makes the deaf hear and the dumb speak.”<verse eid="MRK 7:37" />
    </para>
