  <!--   Chapter  9   -->
  <!--   **********   -->
  <chapter number="9" style="c" sid="MRK 9" />
    <para style="m">
      <verse number="1" style="v" sid="MRK 9:1" />He continued speaking to them:<char style="sup">[A]</char> <char style="wj">“I really mean it when I
        tell you that some who got to stand right here won’t taste death until they get the chance to behold
        God’s involvement with mankind (God’s kingdom) having made its arrival in </char><char style="it"><char
        style="wj">a deluge of miraculous</char></char><char style="wj"> power</char><char style="sup">[a]</char><char
        style="wj">.”</char><verse eid="MRK 9:1" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="2" style="v" sid="MRK 9:2" />Six days later, Jesus took Peter, James, and John with him and brought them to a high mountain, by themselves,
        and he transformed himself in their presence. <verse eid="MRK 9:2" />
      <verse number="3" style="v" sid="MRK 9:3" />His clothing shined a bright white, in a way like no sort of bleach on this planet can whiten. <verse eid="MRK 9:3" />
      <verse number="4" style="v" sid="MRK 9:4" />Elijah and Moses together as a pair appeared to them, and they were having a conversation with Jesus.<verse eid="MRK 9:4" />
      <verse number="5" style="v" sid="MRK 9:5" />Peter thought a bit and said to Jesus, “Jesus—good thing we’re here with you. We’ll make three little
        holy edifices<char style="sup">[b]</char>: one for you, one for Moses, and one for Elijah.” <verse eid="MRK 9:5" />
      <verse number="6" style="v" sid="MRK 9:6" />The fact is, he didn’t know what to say; they had become terrified indeed. <verse eid="MRK 9:6" />
      <verse number="7" style="v" sid="MRK 9:7" />A cloud appeared, engulfing them in a shadow, and a voice appeared out of the cloud, “This is my Beloved
        Son: listen<char style="sup">[c]</char> to him again and again.” <verse eid="MRK 9:7" />
      <verse number="8" style="v" sid="MRK 9:8" />Suddenly, they looked around and didn’t see anyone else with them except for Jesus only.<verse eid="MRK 9:8" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="9" style="v" sid="MRK 9:9" />While they were descending the mountain, he ordered them not to repeat in detail what had happened to
        anyone, except after the Man<char style="sup">[d]</char> is resurrected from the dead. <verse eid="MRK 9:9" />
      <verse number="10" style="v" sid="MRK 9:10" />They kept the matter to themselves, discussing <char style="it">with one another</char> what to be “resurrected
        from the dead” means. <verse eid="MRK 9:10" />
      <verse number="11" style="v" sid="MRK 9:11" />Questioning him, they said, “Why is it that the designated teachers<char style="sup">[e]</char> say that
        Elijah has to come first?” <verse eid="MRK 9:11" />
      <verse number="12" style="v" sid="MRK 9:12" />In the course of telling them he said, <char style="wj">“Sure—Elijah comes and sets everything right
        again; but how is it that, concerning the Man, </char><char style="it"><char style="wj">the Old Testament</char></char><char
        style="wj"> states that he must suffer greatly and be treated with </char><char style="it"><char style="wj">utter</char></char><char
        style="wj"> contempt? </char><verse eid="MRK 9:12" />
      <verse number="13" style="v" sid="MRK 9:13" /><char style="wj">Anyway—I’m telling you that even Elijah has come</char><char style="sup">[f]</char><char
        style="wj">, and they did to him all the things they had always wanted to do</char><char style="sup">[g]</char><char
        style="wj">, just like it had been recorded about him </char><char style="it"><char style="wj">in the
        Old Testament</char></char><char style="wj">.”</char><verse eid="MRK 9:13" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="14" style="v" sid="MRK 9:14" />Having arrived back at where his disciples were, they saw that a huge crowd had surrounded them and that
        designated teachers were arguing with them. <verse eid="MRK 9:14" />
      <verse number="15" style="v" sid="MRK 9:15" />Straightaway, the entire crowd, seeing them, got in a tizzy, rushed over, and began to hail him. <verse eid="MRK 9:15" />
      <verse number="16" style="v" sid="MRK 9:16" />He asked, <char style="wj">“What seems to be the problem</char><char style="sup">[h]</char><char style="wj">?”</char><verse eid="MRK 9:16" />
      <verse number="17" style="v" sid="MRK 9:17" />Someone in the crowd answered, “Teacher, I brought my son, who has a <char style="it">demonic </char>spirit
        of muteness<char style="sup">[i]</char>, to you. <verse eid="MRK 9:17" />
      <verse number="18" style="v" sid="MRK 9:18" />Whenever it takes control of him, it throws him on the ground, and he foams at the mouth and gnashes
        his teeth<char style="sup">[B]</char>, and he goes rigid, <char style="it">tucking into a fetal position</char><char
        style="sup">[C]</char>. I spoke to your disciples so that they would cast it out, and they weren’t able
        to.” <verse eid="MRK 9:18" />
      <verse number="19" style="v" sid="MRK 9:19" />He answered, <char style="wj">“Oh, this prevailing Zeitgeist</char><char style="sup">[j]</char><char
        style="wj"> of unbelief! How long do I </char><char style="it"><char style="wj">have to</char></char><char
        style="wj"> hold your hand for?</char><char style="sup">[k]</char><char style="wj"> How long do I have
        to put up with you for?—Bring him to me.” </char><verse eid="MRK 9:19" />
      <verse number="20" style="v" sid="MRK 9:20" />They brought him to him, and seeing him, the spirit immediately caused him to go into convulsions, drop
        to the ground, and roll around foaming at the mouth. <verse eid="MRK 9:20" />
      <verse number="21" style="v" sid="MRK 9:21" />He asked his father, <char style="wj">“How long has this been going on?</char>” He said, “Since childhood.<verse eid="MRK 9:21" />
      <verse number="22" style="v" sid="MRK 9:22" />Another thing…a lot of times he throws him into fire and into water<char style="sup">[l]</char>, in order
        to destroy him—so now, if you can do anything, have a heart and help me out here.” <verse eid="MRK 9:22" />
      <verse number="23" style="v" sid="MRK 9:23" />Jesus said to him, <char style="wj">“About that ‘if-you-can-do-anything’ thing: all things are possible
        to the one believing.” </char><verse eid="MRK 9:23" />
      <verse number="24" style="v" sid="MRK 9:24" />Immediately the boy’s father began to say over and over, “I believe—help me with my unbelief!” <verse eid="MRK 9:24" />
      <verse number="25" style="v" sid="MRK 9:25" />Now Jesus, seeing that the crowd rushed on over to join them, dropped the hammer on the demonic spirit<char
        style="sup">[m]</char>, <char style="wj">“I command you, you deaf and dumb spirit: come out of him and
        never reenter</char><char style="sup">[n]</char><char style="wj">.”</char> <verse eid="MRK 9:25" />
      <verse number="26" style="v" sid="MRK 9:26" />He screamed and shook him with one last convulsion and came out. He was laid out like a dead body, so
        much so that many <char style="it">were</char> <char style="it">going around</char> saying that he died.<verse eid="MRK 9:26" />
      <verse number="27" style="v" sid="MRK 9:27" />Jesus grabbed his hand and pulled him up, and he stood up. <verse eid="MRK 9:27" />
      <verse number="28" style="v" sid="MRK 9:28" />After they got to be alone in a house, his disciples asked him, “Why is it that we couldn’t cast it out?”<verse eid="MRK 9:28" />
      <verse number="29" style="v" sid="MRK 9:29" />He said, <char style="wj">“This type can’t be cast out by anyone except by prayer.</char><char style="sup">[D]</char><char
        style="wj">”</char><verse eid="MRK 9:29" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="30" style="v" sid="MRK 9:30" />They left there and started going throughout Galilee, and all the while<char style="it"> </char>didn’t
        want to have any interaction with anyone<char style="sup">[o]</char>, <verse eid="MRK 9:30" />
      <verse number="31" style="v" sid="MRK 9:31" />since he kept on <char style="it">working at</char> getting his disciples up to speed, saying repeatedly,
        <char style="wj">“People are going to take the Man</char><char style="sup">[p]</char><char style="wj">
        into custody, they’ll kill him, and, after he’s dead, he’ll be resurrected in three days.”</char><char
        style="sup">[E]</char><char style="wj"> </char><verse eid="MRK 9:31" />
      <verse number="32" style="v" sid="MRK 9:32" />They weren’t making any sense of the remark and all the while were afraid to ask him <char style="it">about
        it</char>.<verse eid="MRK 9:32" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="33" style="v" sid="MRK 9:33" />They went to Capernaum. When they got back home, he asked, <char style="wj">“What were you trying to
        figure out on the way over?”</char> <verse eid="MRK 9:33" />
      <verse number="34" style="v" sid="MRK 9:34" />They kept quiet, since on the way over they were trying to figure out who among them was number-one.<verse eid="MRK 9:34" />
      <verse number="35" style="v" sid="MRK 9:35" />He took a seat, called the Twelve over, and engages them, <char style="wj">“If someone wants to be number-one,
        he must assume last place out of everyone and become everyone’s servant.” </char><verse eid="MRK 9:35" />
      <verse number="36" style="v" sid="MRK 9:36" />He took a child, stood him in front of them, put his arm around him<char style="sup">[q]</char>, and
        told them, <verse eid="MRK 9:36" />
      <verse number="37" style="v" sid="MRK 9:37" /><char style="wj">”Whoever receives a child, like this one here, as part of their Christian duty</char><char
        style="sup">[r]</char><char style="wj"> receives me, and whoever receives me doesn’t receive me </char><char
        style="it"><char style="wj">per se</char></char><char style="wj"> but receives the One who sent me.”</char><verse eid="MRK 9:37" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="38" style="v" sid="MRK 9:38" />John said to him, “Teacher, we saw a guy casting out demons, <char style="it">assuming to do so</char>
        under your authority<char style="sup">[r]</char>, and we intervened and prevented him from doing it,
        because he’s not one of our trainees nor is he affiliated with us<char style="sup">[s]</char>.” <verse eid="MRK 9:38" />
      <verse number="39" style="v" sid="MRK 9:39" />Jesus said, <char style="wj">“Don’t get in his way, since there is no one, when </char><char style="it"><char
        style="wj">presuming to act</char></char><char style="wj"> under my authority,</char><char style="sup">[r]</char><char
        style="wj"> who will do something supernatural and will </char><char style="it"><char style="wj">then
        </char></char><char style="wj">be able to</char><char style="it"><char style="wj"> </char></char><char
        style="wj">quickly </char><char style="it"><char style="wj">turn </char></char><char style="wj">to bad-mouth
        me. </char><verse eid="MRK 9:39" />
      <verse number="40" style="v" sid="MRK 9:40" /><char style="wj">The fact is, he who’s not against us is in favor of us. </char><verse eid="MRK 9:40" />
      <verse number="41" style="v" sid="MRK 9:41" /><char style="wj">Indeed, if one were to do you a good turn because you are considered to be Christians</char><char
        style="sup">[F]</char><char style="wj">, I tell you for sure that in no uncertain terms would this person
        lose out on the payment that’s coming to him.”</char><verse eid="MRK 9:41" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="42" style="v" sid="MRK 9:42" /><char style="wj">”Whoever tries to trip up or draw into sin</char><char style="sup">[t]</char><char style="wj">
        even the most insignificant person who believes in me, he’d be better off tossed into the ocean </char><char
        style="it"><char style="wj">and standing at the bottom of it</char></char><char style="wj"> with a millstone
        strapped to his neck. </char><verse eid="MRK 9:42" />
      <verse number="43" style="v" sid="MRK 9:43" /><char style="wj">And if your right hand (</char><char style="it"><char style="wj">i.e., whatever thing
        you’re doing</char></char><char style="wj">) causes you to sin</char><char style="sup">[t]</char><char
        style="wj">, chop it off (</char><char style="it"><char style="wj">i.e., quit it—period</char></char><char
        style="wj">): you’re better off going through life maimed than being sent to hell having two hands, into
        the Inextinguishable Fire. </char><verse eid="MRK 9:43" />
      <verse number="44" style="v" sid="MRK 9:44" /><char style="sup">[G]</char><char style="wj"> </char><verse eid="MRK 9:44" />
      <verse number="45" style="v" sid="MRK 9:45" /><char style="wj">And if your foot (</char><char style="it"><char style="wj">i.e., the direction your
        life is going in; what you’re in the habit of doing</char></char><char style="wj">) causes you to sin,
        chop it off: you’re better off going through life lame than to be sent to hell having two feet. </char><verse eid="MRK 9:45" />
      <verse number="46" style="v" sid="MRK 9:46" /><char style="sup">[G]</char><char style="wj"> </char><verse eid="MRK 9:46" />
      <verse number="47" style="v" sid="MRK 9:47" /><char style="wj">And if your eye (</char><char style="it"><char style="wj">i.e.,</char></char><char style="wj">
        </char><char style="it"><char style="wj">what your attention is continuously focused on</char></char><char
        style="wj">) causes you to sin, yank it out: you’re better off going through life with one eye than to
        be sent to hell having both eyes, </char><verse eid="MRK 9:47" />
      <verse number="48" style="v" sid="MRK 9:48" /><char style="wj">where their </char><char style="it"><char style="wj">parasitic</char></char><char style="wj">
        worm </char><char style="it"><char style="wj">infection</char></char><char style="wj"> will never go
        away and the fire won’t go out.</char><char style="sup">[G]</char><verse eid="MRK 9:48" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="49" style="v" sid="MRK 9:49" /><char style="wj">”For all </char><char style="it"><char style="wj">meats roasted</char></char><char style="wj">
        by a fire will be salted.</char><char style="sup">[H]</char><verse eid="MRK 9:49" />
      <verse number="50" style="v" sid="MRK 9:50" /><char style="wj">Salt </char><char style="it"><char style="wj">is</char></char><char style="wj"> good</char><char
        style="sup">[u]</char><char style="wj">. But if the salt loses its saltiness, with what will you season
        </char><char style="it"><char style="wj">the meats</char></char><char style="wj">? You have salt </char><char
        style="it"><char style="wj">embedded</char></char><char style="wj"> in yourselves; live in peace with
        one another.”</char><verse eid="MRK 9:50" />
    </para>
